ex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWhile no supranational institutions exist to govern climate change in North America, a system of cooperation among a diverse range of actors and institutions is currently emerging. Given the range of interests that influence climate policy across political boundaries, can these distinct parts be integrated into a coherent, and ultimately resilient system of regional climate cooperation?Climate Change Policy in North America is the first book to examine how cooperation respecting climate change can emerge within decentralized governance arrangements. Leading scholars from a variety of disciplines provide in-depth case studies of climate cooperation initiatives – such as emissions trading, energy cooperation, climate finance, carbon accounting and international trade – as well as analysis of the institutional, political, and economic conditions that influence climate policy integration.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aClimatic changesxCase studiesxGovernment policyzNorth America. 0aClimatic changesxCase studiesxInternational cooperation. 0aEnvironmental policyxCase studiesxInternational cooperation. 0aEnvironmental policyzNorth AmericavCase studies. 0aEnvironmental policyzNorth AmericaxCase studies. 4aDISCOUNT-B. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Public Policy / Environmental Policy.2bisacsh1 aAbbott, Clint L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCraik, A. Neil , eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aCraik, Neil, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDemerse, Clare, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEtcheverry, José, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1